On 21/09/05, Kevin Lawrence &lt;kevin@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Ilja Preuss wrote:
&gt; &gt; I don&#39;t know how a JVM typically works inside, but I don&#39;t see how you
&gt; can
&gt; &gt; get to this conclusion from your example. I&#39;d rather conclude that the
&gt; class
&gt; &gt; file is not was is meant by &quot;class definition&quot; in this case. It&#39;s
&gt; probably
&gt; &gt; more like an internal representation of the class inside the JVM after
&gt; the
&gt; &gt; class file got loaded.
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; I am sure there is a perfectly reasonable &quot;justification&quot; for why a
&gt; ClassDefNotFoundError makes sense. But it is misleading.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; If a class is not found, the class loader will throw a
&gt; ClassNotFoundException. If something goes wrong during static
&gt; initialization, the VM throws an ExceptionInInitializerException.
&gt; Subsequent attempts to reference the class result in
&gt; NoClassDefFoundError. For some reason, the Error rarely has an error
&gt; message that makes any sense.
&gt;
&gt; We see it all the time in code like this :
&gt;
&gt; static {
&gt; FileReader reader = new FileReader(&quot;my.properties&quot;);
&gt; ......
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; It is very confusing to get a NoClassDefFoundError when the class is
&gt; cleary right there. It is also insidious because tool vendors and
&gt; framework providers have to load and run third party code (colloquially,
&gt; /user code/) and have to bullet proof their own code a little more than
&gt; usual. It&#39;s bad practice to catch Throwable, but if you don&#39;t it&#39;s
&gt; likely that Errors will leak out. We end up catching throwable and
&gt; rethrowing certain Errors.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I agree with you that Errors should represent unrecoverable system
&gt; errors. NoClassDefFoundError is not one of those. Neither is
&gt; OutOfMemoryError nor StackOverflowError.


Interesting. Do you catch OutOfMemory problems in your application code?

In the OP&#39;s case, I would wager that a class really was not found and
&gt; that the ClassNotFoundException caused a static initializer to fail
&gt; which caused a ClassDefNotFoundError.
&gt;
&gt; Kevin
